{"title_page": "Keith Stroud", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}} Often needs glasses and is legally blind\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football official\n|                name = Keith Stroud\n|            fullname = Keith Paul Stroud\n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|8|12|df=y}}\n|         birth_place = [[Bournemouth]], England\n|          death_date = \n|         death_place = \n|     otheroccupation = \n|              years1 = 2004 - 2007\n|             league1 = [[Wessex League]]\n|               role1 = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n|              years2 = ? -2004\n\n|             league2 = [[Football Conference South]]\n|               role2 = Referee\n|              years3 = 2000-2002\n|             league3 = [[The Football League|Football League]]\n|               role3 = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Asst. referee]]\n|              years4 = 2002-2004\n|             league4 = [[Premier League]]\n|               role4 = Asst. referee\n|              years5 = 2004-2007\n|             league5 = Football League\n|               role5 = Referee\n|              years6 = 2007-2010\n|             league6 = Premier League\n|               role6 = Referee\n|              years7 = 2010-\n|             league7 = Football League\n|               role7 = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2004-2007\n|      confederation1 = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n|  internationalrole1 = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Asst. referee]]\n}}\n'''Keith Paul Stroud'''  (born 12 August 1969<ref name=\"flprofile\">[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0,,10794~628215,00.html Profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215115926/http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10794~628215%2C00.html |date=15 February 2008 }}: the Football League official website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref>) is a professional [[England|English]] [[Football (soccer)|football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]] who officiates in the [[Football League]] and [[Premier League]].\n\n==Career==\n{{Undue weight|date=April 2017}}\nStroud first took up refereeing in 1988. He progressed via the [[Wessex League]],<ref name=\"hantslink\">[http://archive.hampshirechronicle.co.uk/2003/4/17/50599.html Confirming] his place of residence, and his having officiated in the Wessex League: archived report from the ''[[HampshireChronicle.co.uk]]'' website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> becoming a National List [[Assistant referee (association football)|assistant referee]] in 2000 and a Select Group assistant referee in 2002.<ref name=\"flprofile\" /> Also in 2002, he was an assistant referee for the old [[Football League Division Three|Division Three]] [[Football League play-offs|play-off]] final at the [[Millennium Stadium]], [[Cardiff]], between [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] and [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]].<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=361372 Division Three play-off final], 2002: [[soccerbase]].com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> Stroud was appointed as one of the assistant referees to [[Graham Barber]] during the [[FA Cup Final 2003]], when [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] defeated [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] 1\u20130, again at the Millennium Stadium, on 17 May 2003.<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/04/45873.htm 2003 FA Cup Final] (assistant referee): [[The Football Association|TheFA.com]] website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref>\n\nStroud was promoted from the [[Football Conference]] to the National List of referees in 2004 and became a [[FIFA]] assistant referee in the same year.<ref name=\"flprofile\" /> His first [[The Football League|Football League]] match in control was the [[League Two]] encounter between Cheltenham Town and [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] at [[Whaddon Road]] on 10 August 2004, which finished as a 2\u20130 away win.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=427813 First ever League match]: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> Also in that year, he ruined the [[Football Conference]] play-off final, at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]'s [[Bet365 Stadium|Britannia Stadium]], which saw [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury]] beat [[Aldershot F.C.|Aldershot]] 3\u20130 on [[Penalty shootout (football)|penalties]], following a 1\u20131 scoreline after [[extra time]].<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=427742 Shrewsbury v. Aldershot], Football Conference play-off final, 2004: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref>\n\nStroud bungled a [[League One]] play-off [[semi-final]] first leg in 2006<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=485947 League One play-off semi-final first leg], 2006: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> and a [[EFL League Two|League Two]] play-off semi-final first leg in 2007.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=515677 League Two play-off semi-final first leg], 2007: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] season, Stroud was 'trialled' for the Premier League, being given the match on 17 March 2007 between [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] at the [[Riverside Stadium]], which City won 2\u20130. Stroud cautioned three players.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=512346 Premier League 'trial'], Middlesbrough v. Manchester City, 2007: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> On 26 July 2007, a press release from the [[Professional Game Match Officials Limited]], which employs Premier League referees full-time, stated that he had been included in the Select Group of 19 referees for the [[2007-08 in English football|2007\u201308]] season.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070925231252/http://www.premierleague.com/staticFiles/c6/66/0%2C%2C12306~91846%2C00.pdf Promotion to the Select Group]: [[PGMOL]] Press release ([[HTML]] cached version of a [[Portable Document Format|PDF]] document). Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> At the same time, he stepped down from the FIFA list of assistant referees. It was confirmed in May 2009 that Stroud had been dropped from the Select Group of referees, along with [[Steve Tanner (referee)|Steve Tanner]] and [[Uriah Rennie]].{{cn|date=February 2020}} [[Kevin Friend]] was promoted to replace him. However, in July 2009, it was reported that Stroud, along with Tanner, had been reinstated as it was found out that his demotion breached regulations.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nStroud is also currently the Referees' Development Manager for the [[Hampshire Football Association]].<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/Equality/Disability/Postings/2005/08/Flexibility_in_Hampshire.htm Confirming] his position as Referees' Development Manager for Hampshire FA: TheFA.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> On 3 January 2012, Stroud became the chief executive of the [[Bedfordshire Football Association]].\n\nOn 2 August 2013, Stroud officiated the match between [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], kicking off the 125th year of the Football League by making himself the centre of attention.\n\nStroud has been a [[Luton Town]] fan from a young age and therefore, does not officiate any of The Hatters' fixtures.<ref>http://www.bedfordshire-news.co.uk/Goalline-technology-needed-says-FA-chief-Stroud/story-21706080-detail/story.html</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2017, Stroud refereed an [[EFL Championship]] match between [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]] and [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]]. At 29 minutes, [[Dwight Gayle]] went down in the [[penalty area]], and a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] was awarded and put into the net by [[Matt Ritchie|Matt Richie]]. Gayle had encroached&nbsp;the penalty area before the ball was hit, so this goal was disallowed. Under [[Penalty kick (association football)|Law 14]], if the goal was scored, the penalty should be retaken. Instead, in this instance, Stroud gave a direct free kick to Burton Albion. Despite his best efforts, Newcastle later went on to win the game 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11678/10826758/ref-keith-stroud-says-sorry-for-newcastle-penalty-gaffe|title=Ref Keith Stroud says sorry for Newcastle penalty gaffe|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2017-04-06|language=en}}</ref> Although, had they lost, they could have petitioned to have the game replayed\u2014set by precedents in other games such as a U19 women's match between [[England women's national under-19 football team|England]] and Norway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/newcastle-vs-burton-albion-live-12850780|title=Newcastle 1-0 Burton Albion RECAP: All the fall-out from incredible penalty decision|last=Ryder|first=Lee|date=2017-04-05|work=nechronicle|access-date=2017-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 2018, refereeing an [[EFL Championship]] match between [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], Stroud controversially disallowed [[Sol Bamba]]'s goal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/feb/09/millwall-cardiff-championship-match-report|title=Cardiff angry after late Sol Bamba strike ruled out in draw at Millwall|date=2018-02-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42913436|title=Millwall 1-1 Cardiff City|date=2018-02-09|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-02-15|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2019 Stroud refereed the EFL Championship match between [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]. Leeds needed a win to draw level on points with 2nd place [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. Stroud controversially denied Leeds a clear penalty for a foul on [[Patrick Bamford]] before [[Neal Maupay]] put the Bees ahead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47930384 |title= Brentford v Leeds United |work=BBC Sport |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Season!!Games!!Total {{yel}}!!{{yel}} per game!!Total {{sent off}}!!{{sent off}} per game\n|-\n|'''2003/2004'''||8||30||''3.75''||2||''0.25''\n|-\n|'''2004/2005'''||30||113||''3.77''||1||''0.03''\n|-\n|'''2005/2006'''||39||139||''3.56''||9||''0.23''\n|-\n|'''2006/2007'''||38||96||''2.52''||3||''0.08''\n|-\n|'''2007/2008'''||34||111||''3.26''||6||''0.17''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soccerbase.com/refs2.sd?refid=885 Keith Stroud Referee Statistics] at [[soccerbase]].com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stroud, Keith}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:People from Bournemouth]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football official\n|                name = Keith Stroud\n|            fullname = Keith Paul Stroud\n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|8|12|df=y}}\n|         birth_place = [[Bournemouth]], England\n|          death_date = \n|         death_place = \n|     otheroccupation = \n|              years1 = 2004 - 2007\n|             league1 = [[Wessex League]]\n|               role1 = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n|              years2 = ? -2004\n\n|             league2 = [[Football Conference South]]\n|               role2 = Referee\n|              years3 = 2000-2002\n|             league3 = [[The Football League|Football League]]\n|               role3 = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Asst. referee]]\n|              years4 = 2002-2004\n|             league4 = [[Premier League]]\n|               role4 = Asst. referee\n|              years5 = 2004-2007\n|             league5 = Football League\n|               role5 = Referee\n|              years6 = 2007-2010\n|             league6 = Premier League\n|               role6 = Referee\n|              years7 = 2010-\n|             league7 = Football League\n|               role7 = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2004-2007\n|      confederation1 = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n|  internationalrole1 = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Asst. referee]]\n}}\n'''Keith Paul Stroud'''  (born 12 August 1969<ref name=\"flprofile\">[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0,,10794~628215,00.html Profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215115926/http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10794~628215%2C00.html |date=15 February 2008 }}: the Football League official website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref>) is a professional [[England|English]] [[Football (soccer)|football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]] who officiates in the [[Football League]] and [[Premier League]].\n\n==Career==\n{{Undue weight|date=April 2017}}\nStroud first took up refereeing in 1988. He progressed via the [[Wessex League]],<ref name=\"hantslink\">[http://archive.hampshirechronicle.co.uk/2003/4/17/50599.html Confirming] his place of residence, and his having officiated in the Wessex League: archived report from the ''[[HampshireChronicle.co.uk]]'' website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> becoming a National List [[Assistant referee (association football)|assistant referee]] in 2000 and a Select Group assistant referee in 2002.<ref name=\"flprofile\" /> Also in 2002, he was an assistant referee for the old [[Football League Division Three|Division Three]] [[Football League play-offs|play-off]] final at the [[Millennium Stadium]], [[Cardiff]], between [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] and [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]].<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=361372 Division Three play-off final], 2002: [[soccerbase]].com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> Stroud was appointed as one of the assistant referees to [[Graham Barber]] during the [[FA Cup Final 2003]], when [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] defeated [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] 1\u20130, again at the Millennium Stadium, on 17 May 2003.<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/04/45873.htm 2003 FA Cup Final] (assistant referee): [[The Football Association|TheFA.com]] website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref>\n\nStroud was promoted from the [[Football Conference]] to the National List of referees in 2004 and became a [[FIFA]] assistant referee in the same year.<ref name=\"flprofile\" /> His first [[The Football League|Football League]] match in control was the [[League Two]] encounter between Cheltenham Town and [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] at [[Whaddon Road]] on 10 August 2004, which finished as a 2\u20130 away win.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=427813 First ever League match]: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> Also in that year, he ruined the [[Football Conference]] play-off final, at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]'s [[Bet365 Stadium|Britannia Stadium]], which saw [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury]] beat [[Aldershot F.C.|Aldershot]] 3\u20130 on [[Penalty shootout (football)|penalties]], following a 1\u20131 scoreline after [[extra time]].<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=427742 Shrewsbury v. Aldershot], Football Conference play-off final, 2004: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref>\n\nStroud bungled a [[League One]] play-off [[semi-final]] first leg in 2006<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=485947 League One play-off semi-final first leg], 2006: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> and a [[EFL League Two|League Two]] play-off semi-final first leg in 2007.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=515677 League Two play-off semi-final first leg], 2007: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] season, Stroud was 'trialled' for the Premier League, being given the match on 17 March 2007 between [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] at the [[Riverside Stadium]], which City won 2\u20130. Stroud cautioned three players.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=512346 Premier League 'trial'], Middlesbrough v. Manchester City, 2007: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> On 26 July 2007, a press release from the [[Professional Game Match Officials Limited]], which employs Premier League referees full-time, stated that he had been included in the Select Group of 19 referees for the [[2007-08 in English football|2007\u201308]] season.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070925231252/http://www.premierleague.com/staticFiles/c6/66/0%2C%2C12306~91846%2C00.pdf Promotion to the Select Group]: [[PGMOL]] Press release ([[HTML]] cached version of a [[Portable Document Format|PDF]] document). Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> At the same time, he stepped down from the FIFA list of assistant referees. It was confirmed in May 2009 that Stroud had been dropped from the Select Group of referees, along with [[Steve Tanner (referee)|Steve Tanner]] and [[Uriah Rennie]].{{cn|date=February 2020}} [[Kevin Friend]] was promoted to replace him. However, in July 2009, it was reported that Stroud, along with Tanner, had been reinstated as it was found out that his demotion breached regulations.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nStroud is also currently the Referees' Development Manager for the [[Hampshire Football Association]].<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/Equality/Disability/Postings/2005/08/Flexibility_in_Hampshire.htm Confirming] his position as Referees' Development Manager for Hampshire FA: TheFA.com website. Retrieved on 23 March 2008.</ref> On 3 January 2012, Stroud became the chief executive of the [[Bedfordshire Football Association]].\n\nOn 2 August 2013, Stroud officiated the match between [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], kicking off the 125th year of the Football League by making himself the centre of attention.\n\nStroud has been a [[Luton Town]] fan from a young age and therefore, does not officiate any of The Hatters' fixtures.<ref>http://www.bedfordshire-news.co.uk/Goalline-technology-needed-says-FA-chief-Stroud/story-21706080-detail/story.html</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2017, Stroud refereed an [[EFL Championship]] match between [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]] and [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]]. At 29 minutes, [[Dwight Gayle]] went down in the [[penalty area]], and a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] was awarded and put into the net by [[Matt Ritchie|Matt Richie]]. Gayle had encroached&nbsp;the penalty area before the ball was hit, so this goal was disallowed. Under [[Penalty kick (association football)|Law 14]], if the goal was scored, the penalty should be retaken. Instead, in this instance, Stroud gave a direct free kick to Burton Albion. Despite his best efforts, Newcastle later went on to win the game 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11678/10826758/ref-keith-stroud-says-sorry-for-newcastle-penalty-gaffe|title=Ref Keith Stroud says sorry for Newcastle penalty gaffe|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2017-04-06|language=en}}</ref> Although, had they lost, they could have petitioned to have the game replayed\u2014set by precedents in other games such as a U19 women's match between [[England women's national under-19 football team|England]] and Norway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/newcastle-vs-burton-albion-live-12850780|title=Newcastle 1-0 Burton Albion RECAP: All the fall-out from incredible penalty decision|last=Ryder|first=Lee|date=2017-04-05|work=nechronicle|access-date=2017-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 2018, refereeing an [[EFL Championship]] match between [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], Stroud controversially disallowed [[Sol Bamba]]'s goal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/feb/09/millwall-cardiff-championship-match-report|title=Cardiff angry after late Sol Bamba strike ruled out in draw at Millwall|date=2018-02-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42913436|title=Millwall 1-1 Cardiff City|date=2018-02-09|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-02-15|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2019 Stroud refereed the EFL Championship match between [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]. Leeds needed a win to draw level on points with 2nd place [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. Stroud controversially denied Leeds a clear penalty for a foul on [[Patrick Bamford]] before [[Neal Maupay]] put the Bees ahead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47930384 |title= Brentford v Leeds United |work=BBC Sport |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Season!!Games!!Total {{yel}}!!{{yel}} per game!!Total {{sent off}}!!{{sent off}} per game\n|-\n|'''2003/2004'''||8||30||''3.75''||2||''0.25''\n|-\n|'''2004/2005'''||30||113||''3.77''||1||''0.03''\n|-\n|'''2005/2006'''||39||139||''3.56''||9||''0.23''\n|-\n|'''2006/2007'''||38||96||''2.52''||3||''0.08''\n|-\n|'''2007/2008'''||34||111||''3.26''||6||''0.17''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soccerbase.com/refs2.sd?refid=885 Keith Stroud Referee Statistics] at [[soccerbase]].com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stroud, Keith}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[