008\n*Record receipts: \u00a3499,099 Vs. [[FC Bayern Munich]] in [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] quarter final 2nd leg, 19 March 1996\n*Longest sequence of league wins: 7, wins from 9 May 1922 to 1 September 1922\n*Longest sequence of league defeats: 14, losses from 21 March 1913 to 27 September 1913\n*Longest sequence of unbeaten league matches: 42, from 26 November 1977 to 25 November 1978\n*Longest sequence of league games without a win: 19, from 8 September 1998 to 16 January 1999\n*Longest sequence of league games without a goal: 7, 13 December 2003 to 7 February 2004 and 26 November 2011 to 31 December 2011\n*Quickest goal:\n**League: 14 seconds,<ref>{{cite news|title=Nottm For 1 Norwich 1|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/cc_championship/nottingham_forest/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/00/03/08/SOCCER_Forest_Nightlead.html&TEAMHD=forest&DIV=nat1&TEAM=NOTTINGHAM--FOREST&RH=Nottingham--Forest&PREV_SEASON=1998|work=Sporting Life|first=Jim|last=van Wijk}}</ref> [[Jack Lester]] vs [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], 8 March 2000\n**League Cup: 23 seconds,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10308~1115463,00.html |title=Nottingham Forest 2 v 3 Leicester City |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=19 September 2007 |accessdate=2 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722131539/http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10308~1115463,00.html |archivedate=22 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Paul Smith (footballer born 1979)|Paul Smith]] vs [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], 18 September 2007 in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]].\u00b9\n*Record win (in all competitions): 14\u20130, Vs. [[Clapton F.C.|Clapton]] (away), 1st round [[FA Cup]], 17 January 1891\n*Record defeat (in all competitions): 1\u20139, Vs. [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], Division 2, 10 April 1937\n*Most league points in one season\n**2 points for a win (46 games): 70, Division 3 South, 1950\u201351 \n**2 points for a win (42 Games): 64, Division 1. 1977-78\n**3 points for a win: 94, Division 1, 1997\u201398\n*Most league goals in one season: 110, Division 3, 1950\u201351\n*Highest league scorer in one season: [[Wally Ardron]], 36, Division 3 (South), 1950\u201351\n*Most internationally capped player: [[Stuart Pearce]], 76 for [[England national football team|England]] (78 total)\n*Youngest league player: [[Craig Westcarr]], 16 years, Vs. [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] 13 October 2001\n*Oldest league player: [[Dave Beasant]], 42 years 47 days, Vs. [[Tranmere Rovers]] 6 May 2001\n*Largest transfer fee paid: \u00a313,200,000 to [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] for [[Jo\u00e3o Carvalho]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Joao Carvalho and Diogo Goncalves complete Nottingham Forest moves...|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44482778|work=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018 }}</ref>\n*Largest transfer fee received: \u00a315,000,000 from [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] for [[Britt Assombalonga]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Britt Assombalonga completes \u00a315m move from Nottingham Forest to Middlesbrough|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/done-deal-britt-assombalonga-completes-14m-move-from-nottingham-forest-to-middlesbrough/story-30444601-detail/story.html|work=Nottingham Post |date=17 July 2017 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n\u00b9 By agreement with [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], the game was a replay as the original match three weeks previous was abandoned at half time, due to the collapse of Leicester player [[Clive Clarke]], with Forest leading 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|title=Forest get a freebie but Clemence clinches it late for Leicester|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/sep/19/match.leicestercity|work=The Guardian |date=19 September 2007|first=Richard|last=Rae|accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==European record==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!  style=\"width:244px; background:#d00; color:#fff